@Red Team Simulation vs. Blue Team Analysis
#System Information
OS: CentOS 7 (Kernel 3.10)
Objective: Attack technique mechanics and forensic artifact identification

@Initial Access & Enumeration
#Red Team Actions
Port enumeration -> ss -tulpn
Identify UID 0 users -> cat /etc/passwd | grep :0:
SUID file search -> find / -perm -4000 -type f
Sudo privilege check -> sudo -l
#Blue Team Artifacts
Sudo usage logs in /var/log/secure
Process execution tracking in audit.log
Note: Local enumeration is stealthy; detection requires HIDS/EDR correlation
#Conclusion
Enumeration targets the attack surface; detection depends on event correlation

@Privilege Escalation – SUID Backdoor
#Red Team Actions
Execution: cp /bin/bash /tmp/.sysbash; chmod 4755 /tmp/.sysbash
Trigger: /tmp/.sysbash -p -> grants instant root shell without password
#Blue Team Artifacts
New SUID binary in non-standard location (/tmp)
Timestamp modifications on system binaries
auditd alerts for chmod operations on sensitive paths
#Detection
Command: find / -perm -4000 -type f -> identifies illegitimate SUID files

@Persistence Mechanisms
#Cron Job Injection
Action: Scheduled task creation in /etc/crontab or /var/spool/cron/
Artifact: New entries in /var/log/cron; modified timestamps on cron directories
#SSH Key Injection
Action: Appending rogue public key to ~/.ssh/authorized_keys
Artifact: Log entries in /var/log/secure showing "Accepted publickey"
Conclusion: New SSH keys in production are critical security events

@Defense Evasion & Obfuscation
#History Tampering
Action: history -c; unset HISTFILE
Blue Insight: Only clears current bash session history; does not affect sudo logs or auditd
#Process Hiding
Action: Renaming binaries (e.g., cp /bin/sleep /tmp/.kworker)
Artifact: Processes running from /tmp or /dev/shm; identifiable via /proc/[PID]/exe
Conclusion: Any process executing from world-writable directories is highly suspicious

@Key Security Takeaways
#Attack Mechanics
Attacks rely on misconfigurations (SUID, weak permissions, cron, SSH keys)
Every action leaves a footprint: timestamps, log entries, or file changes
#Detection Strategy
Requires a system baseline to identify "normal" vs. "malicious" behavior
Continuous auditing of UID 0 accounts and file integrity (e.g., AIDE)
#Competency Shift
Focus moves from basic IT support to Analytical Security Thinking
Understanding the "why" behind system artifacts and privilege escalation
